For comparison, we consider MRTP and random scheduling as benchmark. Note that these are the optimal strategies, respectively, from the latency and fairness perspectives. In Fig. 1, we compare the convergence behaviour of the OF-MRTP, A-MRTP and MRTP schemes. As one would expect, the test accuracy increases faster with MRTP; however, due to the non-iid distribution of the data it converges to a sub-optimal model and eventually diverges111The test accuracy is plotted until the divergence point.. While A-MRTP eventually reaches an accuray level above MRTP (see Table II), it introduces significant latency due to scheduling the clients with poor channel conditions to reduce their age. The convergence behaviour of random scheduling is not included in the figure since the average per-round latency is very high, instead, we compare OF-MRTP and random scheduling based on the final test accuracy results which is averaged over 10 trails. We observe that the average final test accuracy with random scheduling is 83.92Â±0.37plus-or-minus83.920.3783.92\pm 0.37. In comparison with the test accuracy results in Table I, we can conclude that OF-MRTP does not compromise the accuracy while significantly reducing the latency.
